a lot of
people are willing to go.

21:40.866 --> 21:46.605 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But North Carolina, for
instance, is a state
certainly where the Clinton
campaign believes

21:46.639 --> 21:49.141 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that they have a chance to win
this.

21:49.175 --> 21:51.744 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And if they can, that would be a
huge problem
for Donald Trump.

21:51.777 --> 21:55.781 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Susan, just
quickly, your
newspaper had a poll today
looking at millennials

21:55.814 --> 21:57.516 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that vote, young voters under
35.

21:57.550 --> 22:02.121 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SUSAN PAGE: And the historic
weakness by Donald
Trump among these younger
voters.

22:02.154 --> 22:05.191 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's only getting 20 percent of
the vote of
millennials.

22:05.224 --> 22:07.893 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, they are the least reliable
voters by
age.

22:07.927 --> 22:09.995 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Older people are more likely to
turn out to
the polls.

22:10.029 --> 22:14.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But we have never seen a
candidate in modern
times have that poor a showing
of millennials.

22:14.633 --> 22:18.837 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if that trend continues, it
will be the
third consecutive election where
Democrats

22:18.871 --> 22:22.741 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
will have beaten the Republican
by double
digits among younger voters.

22:22.775 --> 22:27.012 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if you look at the long-term
future of
this party, that starts to set
partisan preferences

22:27.046 --> 22:29.114 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in a way that's really dangerous
for the GOP.

22:29.148 --> 22:32.151 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Hillary
Clinton, Tamara
Keith, was out on the trail
today with Vice

22:32.184 --> 22:38.090 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Biden, working-class
Scranton, Pennsylvania,
on a day when Donald Trump is
out hammering

22:38.123 --> 22:40.326 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
away on national security, on
ISIS.

22:40.359 --> 22:43.429 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Is she as vulnerable as Donald
Trump makes
her out to be?

22:43.462 --> 22:47.299 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He at one point said, she's not
capable of
handling ISIS.

22:47.333 --> 22:51.904 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TAMARA KEITH: He also implied
that she may
not be healthy enough to handle
ISIS.

22:51.937 --> 22:55.374 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There was a little bit of that
in there.

22:55.407 --> 23:01.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is an area where sometimes
she doesn't
talk about it with the urgency
that he talks

23:01.847 --> 23:05.618 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about it, and that might give
him a little
bit of space.

23:05.651 --> 23:12.024 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But many polls are now showing
that people
believe Hillary Clinton does
have the temperament

23:12.057 --> 23:15.961 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on foreign policy in a way that
some voters
have concerns about Donald
Trump.

23:15.995 --> 23:19.531 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But he does come
back to that
language, Susan, time and again,
suggesting

23:19.565 --> 23:23.602 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that she just -- she wouldn't be
capable,
she wouldn't be strong enough to
stand up

23:23.636 --> 23:25.371 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to something like ISIS.

23:25.404 --> 23:27.373 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SUSAN PAGE: And if you want to
look at the
biggest problem Hillary Clinton
has, it's

23:27.406 --> 23:31.277 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that this is an electorate that
wants change,
wants change in terms of the
battle against

23:31.310 --> 23:36.982 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
terrorism, wants change in terms
of the growing
equality in the U.S. system.

23:37.016 --> 23:41.387 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so there is an argument to
be made against
Hillary Clinton, who is, as
Donald Trump would

23:41.420 --> 23:43.555 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
say, a third term of Barack
Obama.

23:43.589 --> 23:48.227 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The question is, is Donald Trump
the person
who can prosecute the case
against Hillary

23:48.260 --> 23:49.461 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Clinton?

23:49.495 --> 23:51.230 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Tamara, what
do we think
about that?

23:51.263 --> 23:57.536 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Is -- because if he does -- say
he gives a
speech about ISIS every other
day between

23:57.569 --> 23:59.838 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
now and the election.

23:59.872 --> 24:01.974 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Can that -- is that the kind of
thing that
can move voters?

24:02.007 --> 24:05.377 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TAMARA KEITH: Well, I mean, he
would have
to do just those.

24:05.411 --> 24:07.212 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Speeches.

24:07.246 --> 24:09.648 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TAMARA KEITH: He would have to
do just the
teleprompter, and not the big
raucous rallies

24:09.682 --> 24:14.086 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
where he gets -- that, really,
they fuel him
and they give him a ton of
energy.

24:14.119 --> 24:20.059 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But at those raucous rallies, a
more nuanced
argument about whether the Iraq
pullout should

24:20.092 --> 24:26.098 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have happened at the pace that
it did becomes
Barack Obama founded ISIS, and
then becomes,

24:26.131 --> 24:31.103 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you know, a day of doubling
down, and then
a day of tweeting about sarcasm.

24:31.136 --> 24:33.939 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, just
quickly, Susan, it's
not just that.

24:33.972 --> 24:36.742 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's -- he will keep coming back
to the e-mails,
the 30,000 e-mails.

24:36.775 --> 24:38.410 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He brings it up every chance he
gets.

24:38.444 --> 24:39.411 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
SUSAN PAGE: That's right.

24:39.445 --> 24:42.014 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that is a vulnerability for
Hillary Clinton.

24:42.047 --> 24:47.252 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But her attack on him is that he
doesn't have
the temperament or the
disposition to handle

24:47.286 --> 24:49.021 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the job of president.

24:49.054 --> 24:52.725 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And especially when it comes to
the issue
of commander in chief, that is
an argument

24:52.758 --> 24:54.927 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that has gotten some traction
with American
voters.

24:54.960 --> 25:02.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Susan Page,
Tamara Keith, thank
you both very much, 85 days to
go.

25:02.701 --> 25:04.136 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

25:04.169 --> 25:10.109 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
TAMARA KEITH: Countdown clock.

25:10.142 --> 25:13.946 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

25:13.979 --> 25:19.952 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour": Are
we safer
now than we were on 9/11?; and
photography

25:19.985 --> 25:24.823 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that makes us rethink privacy in
a world full
of cameras.

25:24.857 --> 25:32.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, first: The years-long fight
to control
Syria's largest city, Aleppo,
grinds on, with

25:32.097 --> 25:35.901 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
civilians stuck between rebel
and government
forces.

25:35.934 --> 25:41.440 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Last week, more than two dozen
Syrian physicians
there wrote a letter to
President Obama urging

25:41.473 --> 25:44.276 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
him to take action to end the
carnage.

25:44.309 --> 25:48.414 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Only 35 physicians remain to
serve more than
300,000 people.

25:48.447 --> 25:54.219 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They wrote, in part, because
they themselves
are under attack, the people
whose mission

25:54.253 --> 25:58.123 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it is to help the civilians
caught in the
crossfire.

25:58.157 --> 26:04.163 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they are hit in the places
that should
be safest, hospitals and other
medical facilities.

26:04.196 --> 26:09.835 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Special correspondent Marcia
Biggs reports
now from Southern Turkey near
the Syrian border.

26:09.868 --> 26:14.406 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And a warning: This story
contains images
that may upset some viewers.

26:14.440 --> 26:21.246 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: It is a war crime
to target
medical facilities, but, in
Syria, bombs rain

26:21.280 --> 26:25.083 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
down on hospitals, doctors and
patients.

26:25.117 --> 26:30.155 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Just in the last few weeks,
pro-government
forces bombed a maternity
hospital in Idlib,

26:30.189 --> 26:31.990 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
supported by Save the Children.

26:32.024 --> 26:35.561 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And airstrikes hit six hospitals
around Aleppo.

26:35.594 --> 26:41.900 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Nurses gathered babies from
their incubators,
the strike narrowly missing
their ward.

26:41.934 --> 26:44.970 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Rami Kalazi is no stranger to
airstrikes like
these.

26:45.003 --> 26:46.638 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

26:46.672 --> 26:48.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RAMI KALAZI, Forced to Leave
Syria: I was
sleeping here, and my colleague
is here.

26:48.207 --> 26:50.175 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And the attack happened.

26:50.209 --> 26:51.777 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We came out alive.

26:51.810 --> 26:53.145 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I don't know how.

26:53.178 --> 26:56.882 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Kalazi was one of
Aleppo's last
remaining doctors.

26:56.915 --> 26:58.784 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We caught up with him in Turkey.

26:58.817 --> 27:01.487 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He said he believes these
hospitals were targeted.

27:01.520 --> 27:02.654 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

27:02.688 --> 27:05.023 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RAMI KALAZI: They are the artery
of life in
the city.

27:05.057 --> 27:07.292 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Can you imagine a life in city
without hospitals?

27:07.326 --> 27:09.394 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Who will treat your kids?

27:09.428 --> 27:13.332 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Who will make the surgeries for
the injured
people?

27:13.365 --> 27:18.871 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, they are targeting these
hospitals because
they know, if these hospitals
were completely

27:18.904 --> 27:21.573 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
destroyed, the life will be
completely destroyed.

27:21.607 --> 27:27.312 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Eastern Aleppo had
already suffered
a massive blow in April, when Al
Quds Hospital,

27:27.346 --> 27:32.584 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
supported by Doctors Without
Borders, and
the city's main pediatric
hospital, was destroyed

27:32.618 --> 27:34.052 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
by two consecutive airstrikes.

27:34.086 --> 27:35.053 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

27:35.087 --> 27:37.089 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
RAMI KALAZI: It was a very hard
night.

27:37.122 --> 27:42.294 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Every one or two hour, we had an
airstrike,
and we had to treat some injured
people.

27:42.327 --> 27:48.534 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Soon he realized
the full extent
of the damage, more than 50
people dead, including

27:48.567 --> 27:50.302 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
six members of hospital staff.

27:50.335 --> 27:51.303 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

27:51.336 --> 27:52.804 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
RAMI KALAZI: They were all
friends.

27:52.838 --> 27:57.476 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, it was emotionally so hard,
because you
are treating your friend.

27:57.509 --> 27:59.945 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You know how hard is that.

27:59.978 --> 28:05.284 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And you see that he is in
danger, he may not
live, he may not survive.

28:05.317 --> 28:07.085 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It was a horrible night.

28:07.119 --> 28:12.090 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: One of them,
35-year-old Waseem
Maaz, seen here on that fateful
night, was

28:12.124 --> 28:16.795 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a beloved pediatrician, one of
only two in
the entire city.

28:16.828 --> 28:19.231 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He was just beginning his shift.

28:19.264 --> 28:20.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Moments later, disaster.

28:20.899 --> 28:23.001 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What has Syria lost there?

28:23.035 --> 28:24.803 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

28:24.836 --> 28:28.707 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RAMI KALAZI: Can you imagine,
when you have
more than 300,000 people in your
city, and

28:28.740 --> 28:32.578 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you have only two pediatricians,
and you have
lost one?

28:32.611 --> 28:36.448 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Can you imagine how much the
loss is big?

28:36.481 --> 28:41.687 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: According to
Physicians for
Human Rights, there have been
over 375 strikes

28:41.720 --> 28:45.824 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
against medical facilities and
doctors in
Syria since the revolution
began.

28:45.857 --> 28:49.995 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Their report stipulates that
over 90 percent
of those came at the hands of
the Syrian regime

28:50.028 --> 28:51.964 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and its allies.

28:51.997 --> 28:53.765 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WIDNEY BROWN, Director of
Programs, Physicians
for Human Rights: Syria had a
very sophisticated

28:53.799 --> 28:58.770 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
health care infrastructure,
hospitals that
are multistoried, very
well-equipped, very

28:58.804 --> 29:00.672 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
large, very well-marked.

29:00.706 --> 29:04.443 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You don't make a mistake of just
hitting that
hospital, and you certainly
don't do it multiple

29:04.476 --> 29:05.844 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
times.

29:05.877 --> 29:08.213 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is absolutely a deliberate
strategy by
the Syrian government.

29:08.246 --> 29:12.618 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Widney Brown is
director of
programs for the Physicians for
Human Rights,

29:12.651 --> 29:17.990 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
which maintains that the
destruction of hospitals
by President Assad is being used
as a weapon

29:18.023 --> 29:19.758 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
of war.

29:19.791 --> 29:23.061 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WIDNEY BROWN: When you target a
hospital,
you don't just destroy that
brick-and-mortar

29:23.095 --> 29:24.596 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
structure.

29:24.630 --> 29:28.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You destroy actually a safe
place that people
can go for lifesaving aid.

29:28.100 --> 29:31.570 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When you kill a doctor, you
don't just kill
that one individual.

29:31.603 --> 29:34.806 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You actually kill all the people
he or she
would have saved.

29:34.840 --> 29:40.412 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Brown says medical
professionals
are specifically targeted for
detention, torture,

29:40.445 --> 29:47.753 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and even murder by the Syrian
regime; 750
have been killed in the last
five years, like

29:47.786 --> 29:52.157 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
46-year-old cardiologist Hasan
al-Araj, whose
car was hit by an airstrike.

29:52.190 --> 29:56.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WIDNEY BROWN: We believe that
they are being
persecuted because they can
actually give

29:56.361 --> 30:00.732 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
eyewitness testimony about all
of the crimes
being committed by the Syrian
government.

30:00.766 --> 30:05.737 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When they say a chemical weapon
was used,
they are incredibly credible.

30:05.771 --> 30:10.375 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Hospitals are
often hit multiple
times as part of what is called
a double-tap

30:10.409 --> 30:12.310 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
strategy.

30:12.344 --> 30:15.747 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Planes will circle back after
hitting a target,
once first-responders have
arrived on scene,

30:15.781 --> 30:23.388 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as shown on this video, to
target those delivering
aid to the wounded.

30:23.422 --> 30:26.725 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Despite the risks, hospitals
still continue
to run.

30:26.758 --> 30:33.098 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Here, Dr. Kalazi sweeps up after
one of the
more than 20 strikes his
hospital suffered,

30:33.131 --> 30:36.568 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
creating a new normal for an
already ravaged
community.

30:36.601 --> 30:38.136 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

30:38.170 --> 30:40.806 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RAMI KALAZI: All the hospitals
in Aleppo City
have been bombed, all of them.

30:40.839 --> 30:42.207 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
There's no exceptions.

30:42.240 --> 30:47.446 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The first thing you will think
in is looking
for your colleagues.

30:47.479 --> 30:50.315 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Are they still alive or dead?

30:50.348 --> 30:58.423 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Will I see, for example, of an
arm for my
colleague or a leg, or I will
see a body,

30:58.457 --> 31:03.361 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
or half of a body, or will I see
him alive?

31:03.395 --> 31:05.230 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
You don't know.

31:05.263 --> 31:11.269 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We announce among the patients
that it's now
risky to stay in the hospital,
so please find

31:11.303 --> 31:14.873 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
safe places or go as fast as you
can to your
homes.

31:14.906 --> 31:16.675 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: What about the
critical patients?

31:16.708 --> 31:17.676 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

31:17.709 --> 31:18.677 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
RAMI KALAZI: They stay in the
hospital.

31:18.710 --> 31:21.480 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And some of them died during
these attacks.

31:21.513 --> 31:23.749 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: So there's just
really nowhere
to go?

31:23.782 --> 31:24.750 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

31:24.783 --> 31:26.585 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
RAMI KALAZI: No.

31:26.618 --> 31:28.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: You would think
that the hospital
would be the safe place, the
safe zone.

31:28.386 --> 31:29.488 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

31:29.521 --> 31:31.289 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RAMI KALAZI: But, in Syria,
there is nothing
safe.

31:31.323 --> 31:36.128 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Kalazi told us the
memory that
haunts him the most is of a
family of seven

31:36.161 --> 31:37.696 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
pulled from under the rubble.

31:37.729 --> 31:40.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WIDNEY BROWN: Only one survived,
only one
child.

31:40.999 --> 31:43.368 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He was 3 years old.

31:43.401 --> 31:45.771 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I was completely freezed.

31:45.804 --> 31:48.640 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I just cried.

31:48.673 --> 31:53.445 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When I see a child, it's so
hard, because
he's a child.

31:53.478 --> 31:54.446 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
He's innocent.

31:54.479 --> 31:56.515 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He's made nothing to be punished
for.

31:56.548 --> 32:02.120 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Amidst so much
despair, Dr.
Kalazi's wife gave birth to a
baby boy just

32:02.154 --> 32:03.121 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
over a year ago.

32:03.155 --> 32:04.689 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

32:04.723 --> 32:08.860 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RAMI KALAZI: We decided to have
a baby, because
it's like a new hope, you know?

32:08.894 --> 32:17.469 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But we decided to stay in
Aleppo, because
we have a mission to complete.

32:17.502 --> 32:18.603 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We are physicians.

32:18.637 --> 32:20.272 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
We are humans.

32:20.305 --> 32:22.007 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And this is our city.

32:22.040 --> 32:27.579 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: A few months ago,
his hospital
and his home were hit on the
same day.

32:27.612 --> 32:34.085 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Here he is in this video with
his wife and
infant son surveying the damage.

32:34.119 --> 32:41.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Kalazi was on R&amp;R outside the
city last month
when government forces blocked
the last road

32:41.459 --> 32:47.465 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to Aleppo, making it not only
impossible for
him to return, but for the
people to get desperately

32:47.499 --> 32:49.000 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
needed food and medical aid.

32:49.034 --> 32:53.205 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WIDNEY BROWN: What we have in
Syria are two
stories.

32:53.238 --> 32:59.010 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's quick deaths by being
bombed when you're
a civilian, and it's the slow
death of starvation.

32:59.044 --> 33:03.048 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they are facing this as the
U.N. Security
Council does nothing.

33:03.081 --> 33:05.383 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Do you ever feel
abandoned?

33:05.417 --> 33:06.384 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

33:06.418 --> 33:08.086 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
RAMI KALAZI: From the world,
yes.

33:08.119 --> 33:14.259 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
From the international
community, yes, because
they can do, but they don't want
to.

33:14.292 --> 33:17.863 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
No one wants to help us from the
governments.

33:17.896 --> 33:19.531 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We don't know why.

33:19.564 --> 33:22.968 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: But halfway around
the world,
these American doctors do want
to help.

33:23.001 --> 33:24.803 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

33:24.836 --> 33:26.938 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ZAHER SAHLOUL, Syrian American
Medical Society:
So, you have doctors who send,
for example,

33:26.972 --> 33:28.673 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
X-rays.

33:28.707 --> 33:33.645 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Drs. Zaher Sahloul
and Samer
Attar represent the Syrian
American Medical

33:33.678 --> 33:39.451 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Society, which connects doctors
in the U.S.
with Kalazi's hospital and
others all over

33:39.484 --> 33:40.452 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Syria.

33:40.485 --> 33:42.320 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

33:42.354 --> 33:45.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ZAHER SAHLOUL: They can move the
camera from
a patient to patient, and
describe the patient

33:45.290 --> 33:46.958 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to me.

33:46.992 --> 33:48.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They can look at -- put the
camera on the
monitor, so I can see the vital
signs.

33:48.660 --> 33:52.564 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I can communicate with the
doctor also, and
they will tell me what's
happening.

33:52.597 --> 33:56.034 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, that way, you are there, but
through this
very simple technology.

33:56.067 --> 33:57.569 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

33:57.602 --> 34:01.306 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RAMI KALAZI: You are not alone
in treating
your person -- your patients.

34:01.339 --> 34:04.209 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And you have this emotional
support.

34:04.242 --> 34:10.181 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Sahloul and Attar
traveled last
month to Aleppo to show
solidarity with their

34:10.215 --> 34:11.182 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Syrian colleagues.

34:11.216 --> 34:12.717 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

34:12.751 --> 34:13.818 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SAMER ATTAR, Syrian American
Medical Society:
You definitely feel targeted.

34:13.852 --> 34:15.654 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Everyone feels targeted.

34:15.687 --> 34:21.593 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A missile lands somewhere within
the vicinity
of the hospital, and you feel
the foundations

34:21.626 --> 34:23.328 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of the hospital shake.

34:23.361 --> 34:26.598 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There was one moment I was
knocked off my
feet, and your ears are ringing,
but people

34:26.631 --> 34:28.566 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
just get back up and go back to
work.

34:28.600 --> 34:34.606 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're staying out of a sense
of obligation
and duty to help the helpless.

34:34.639 --> 34:37.909 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
They are heroically and
selflessly risking
their lives.

34:37.943 --> 34:42.681 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: They say some
hospitals have
even moved their emergency rooms
underground

34:42.714 --> 34:44.783 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to protect the patients, who
come in droves.

34:44.816 --> 34:45.784 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

34:45.817 --> 34:47.052 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SAMER ATTAR: There were just so
many people.

34:47.085 --> 34:50.555 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It was just child after child
after child
after child.

34:50.588 --> 34:56.061 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you just keep saying to
yourself, just,
please, God, when will this
trail of injured

34:56.094 --> 34:57.262 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
end?

34:57.295 --> 34:58.663 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: Are you angry by
the lack of
response?

34:58.697 --> 34:59.664 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

34:59.698 --> 35:01.199 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SAMER ATTAR: Well, of course
you're angry.

35:01.232 --> 35:04.202 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's five years on, close to
half-a-million
killed and 12 million displaced.

35:04.235 --> 35:06.037 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And those numbers are still
rising.

35:06.071 --> 35:10.608 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And now we have a city of
300,000 people that
are being sieged and starved and
bombed to

35:10.642 --> 35:14.145 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
death, with the international
community sitting
idly by.

35:14.179 --> 35:18.083 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And you have children who are
burning tires
to create their own no-fly zone.

35:18.116 --> 35:19.084 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's embarrassing.

35:19.117 --> 35:20.952 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
That's shameful.

35:20.986 --> 35:24.422 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: The doctors
testified last week
at a U.N. special session on
Aleppo, where

35:24.456 --> 35:29.761 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they conveyed messages from
their Syrian colleagues,
treating babies exposed to
chlorine gas and

35:29.794 --> 35:35.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
toddlers with spines shredded
decimated by
shrapnel, wrapping tiny bodies
in white shrouds.

35:35.834 --> 35:40.005 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
After five long years, one
21-year-old nurse
knows now not to ask for too
much.

35:40.038 --> 35:41.806 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

35:41.840 --> 35:45.410 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SAMER ATTAR: I expected her to
talk about
no-fly zone, or peace, or all of
these things.

35:45.443 --> 35:46.911 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And she said: I have a patient.

35:46.945 --> 35:47.912 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Her name is Shahed.

35:47.946 --> 35:49.781 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
She is 10 years old.

35:49.814 --> 35:54.285 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Is there any way that they can
intervene to
evacuate the patient, so her
life can be saved?

35:54.319 --> 35:57.155 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Because her mom comes every day,
and she tells
her, and she tells her, I would
like to take

35:57.188 --> 36:00.425 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
you home, so you can ride your
bicycle.

36:00.458 --> 36:02.460 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And this is what she wanted from
the Security
Council.

36:02.494 --> 36:07.866 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: While the siege on
Aleppo was
partially broken by rebel
soldiers just over

36:07.899 --> 36:12.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a week ago, the last road in and
out of the
city is still far too dangerous
to travel.

36:12.971 --> 36:19.978 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, Rami Kalazi remains on the
outside looking
in, desperate to get back to his
beloved hometown.

36:20.011 --> 36:21.813 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

36:21.846 --> 36:29.254 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RAMI KALAZI: And any time Aleppo
is not besieged,
I will go back to Aleppo, even
for a visit.

36:29.287 --> 36:32.057 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's my lovely place.

36:32.090 --> 36:34.125 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: It's still your
lovely place.

36:34.159 --> 36:35.994 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

36:36.027 --> 36:41.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RAMI KALAZI: Yes, it's my lovely
place, because
I feel that I'm born to be here
to help these

36:41.866 --> 36:43.501 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
people.

36:43.535 --> 36:49.707 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARCIA BIGGS: A place where no
one is safe
and saving lives can get you
killed.

36:49.741 --> 36:58.483 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Marcia Biggs in
Gaziantep, Southern Turkey.

36:58.516 --> 37:12.964 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And now a look at
the current
state of security inside the
U.S.

37:12.997 --> 37:18.436 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
As we approach the 15th
anniversary of 9/11,
journalist Steven Brill spent
the past year

37:18.470 --> 37:23.741 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
looking into how the country has
changed since
that terrible day, what's been
spent and what

37:23.775 --> 37:25.376 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
gaps still exist.

37:25.410 --> 37:30.181 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
His article, "Are We Any
Safer?", appears
in the latest issue of "The
Atlantic."

37:30.215 --> 37:32.884 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I recently sat down with him
and asked
him what he learned.

37:32.917 --> 37:38.723 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVEN BRILL, "The Atlantic": In
a nutshell,
what I concluded was, the way we
have responded

37:38.756 --> 37:44.729 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to the terrorist attacks, to
9/11, which,
you know, changed everything, is
sort of a

37:44.762 --> 37:47.932 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
microcosm of what we are as a
country today.

37:47.966 --> 37:57.175 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
A lot of it was heroic,
ingenious, people
going beyond the cause of duty,
doing really

37:57.208 --> 37:59.043 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
great things.

37:59.077 --> 38:03.815 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And then a lot of it was
actually quite the
opposite, a lot of Beltway
boondoggles, billions

38:03.848 --> 38:09.821 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of dollars wasted because
government contractors
promised technology and
solutions that they

38:09.854 --> 38:11.589 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
couldn't produce.

38:11.623 --> 38:17.896 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we have struggled as a
country with dealing
with the notion of this new kind
of risk.

38:17.929 --> 38:23.101 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The idea, as President Bush
explained, after
9/11, of never again, we're
never going to

38:23.134 --> 38:28.006 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have a terrorist attack again,
that's just
unrealistic in today's world.

38:28.039 --> 38:33.344 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You clearly give
the government
-- and it spans several
administrations, two

38:33.378 --> 38:36.848 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
administrations -- credit for
getting some
things right, as you just said,
but...

38:36.881 --> 38:40.818 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVEN BRILL: A lot of things
right, and a
lot of unsung people, tens of
thousands of

38:40.852 --> 38:47.592 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people going to work every day
at the Department
of Homeland Security, the FBI,
places like

38:47.625 --> 38:54.032 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TSA, the Border Patrol, really
obsessed with
the job of keeping us safe.

38:54.065 --> 38:58.136 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the only time we notice them
is when something
goes wrong.

38:58.169 --> 38:59.571 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And that makes it a tough job.

38:59.604 --> 39:05.910 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
On the other hand, a lot of it
went back to
politics as usual.

39:05.944 --> 39:13.484 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Every small town that you can
think of made
a request for government grants
for homeland

39:13.518 --> 39:18.856 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
security, for everything ranging
from routine
fire trucks to fish tanks in a
police station.

39:18.890 --> 39:20.892 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, there are a lot of abuses.

39:20.925 --> 39:26.231 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I was struck
because, early
on in the piece, you say, yes,
we are safer

39:26.264 --> 39:31.536 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
than we were on 9/11, safer
against the kind
of threat we faced on 9/11.

39:31.569 --> 39:32.537 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
STEVEN BRILL: Right.

39:32.570 --> 39:33.538 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But the threat
has changed.

39:33.571 --> 39:35.406 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
STEVEN BRILL: Right.

39:35.440 --> 39:37.709 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And that's what
the government
is -- all of us are grappling
with right now.

39:37.742 --> 39:43.181 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVEN BRILL: We have done a lot
to batten
down the hatches, to make us
safer, at the

39:43.214 --> 39:47.418 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
airports, at the ports, all over
the place.

39:47.452 --> 39:51.389 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the threats have multiplied,
the threats
around the world.

39:51.422 --> 39:54.926 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Our defenses are much stronger.

39:54.959 --> 39:57.762 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The offense has multiplied and
is much stronger.

39:57.795 --> 40:02.834 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's more difficult because,
unlike the
kind of coordinated,
orchestrated attack that

40:02.867 --> 40:09.107 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we faced on 9/11, where people
were communicating,
money was exchanging hands, that
kind of stuff

40:09.140 --> 40:14.312 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which we can now track, if some
lone wolf
in his basement is online...

40:14.345 --> 40:16.114 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Right.

40:16.147 --> 40:20.818 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVEN BRILL: ... and he can go
into a gun
store in this country and buy an
assault weapon,

40:20.852 --> 40:27.025 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and he shoots up a shopping mall
and yells
out, you know, something in
Arabic, that makes

40:27.058 --> 40:30.962 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
him a terrorist, and it scares
us mightily.

40:30.995 --> 40:35.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's not something we can
really prevent,
other than doing something about
assault weapons.

40:35.633 --> 40:41.973 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, how -- that's
what interested
me so much in this piece was you
look at one

40:42.006 --> 40:45.109 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
thing after another that the
government did,
some of it successfully.

40:45.143 --> 40:52.183 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, still, you have this
undefined threat
out there, some of which, as you
say, it's

40:52.216 --> 40:53.951 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a lone wolf.

40:53.985 --> 40:58.089 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's somebody who may be just
mentally unstable
who decides to adopt the
terrorism...

40:58.122 --> 40:59.090 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

40:59.123 --> 41:00.825 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
STEVEN BRILL: Exactly.

41:00.858 --> 41:03.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there are some non-lone wolf
threats,
some kind of more orchestrated
threats, that

41:03.728 --> 41:09.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
were in the headlines right
after 9/11 that
basically fell out of the
headlines, and therefore

41:09.133 --> 41:13.805 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
fell off our radar, and,
frankly, that the
government hasn't paid enough
attention to.

41:13.838 --> 41:17.542 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
The best example is the
bioterror attack.

41:17.575 --> 41:19.243 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Bioterrorism.

41:19.277 --> 41:22.914 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVEN BRILL: Right after 9/11,
with the anthrax
attacks, that's all we thought
of.

41:22.947 --> 41:29.087 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The technology that we tried to
develop 15
years ago still hasn't been
developed that

41:29.120 --> 41:33.157 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
would warn us in the right way
of a bio attack.

41:33.191 --> 41:37.962 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have not done enough to
protect ourselves
from dirty bombs.

41:37.995 --> 41:43.634 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You can still go to hospitals
and other industrial
sites all over this country, and
maybe have

41:43.668 --> 41:49.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to break a tiny little padlock,
if that, to
get ahold of radiological
material that you

41:49.440 --> 41:53.277 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
can mix with an easily available
explosive
and create a dirty bomb.

41:53.311 --> 41:56.214 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But why hasn't
something like
that been addressed?

41:56.247 --> 42:00.952 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEVEN BRILL: Because we tend to
go after
yesterday's headline.

42:00.985 --> 42:03.321 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Our attention shifts.

42:03.354 --> 42:10.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we don't -- when you say
that everything's
a priority, if you have 10 or 12
high priorities,

42:10.795 --> 42:16.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
none of them becomes a priority,
except if
it's in the news, if it's in the
headlines,

42:16.234 --> 42:19.337 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
if it's part of a congressional
hearing, maybe.

42:19.370 --> 42:26.811 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, we haven't done the job we
need to do
of really assessing all the
threats rationally

42:26.844 --> 42:31.983 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and having a discussion with the
American
people that says, we can't deal
with everything,

42:32.016 --> 42:37.321 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we have to have priorities, and
some things
are going to slip through the
cracks, and,

42:37.355 --> 42:44.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by the way, there are going to
be terrorist
attacks, not of the kind we had
on 9/11.

42:44.362 --> 42:50.435 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
People are never going to be
able to hijack
a plane because of the TSA,
because we have

42:50.468 --> 42:52.503 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
fortified cockpit doors in
airlines.

42:52.537 --> 42:58.543 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have done a lot of things to
deal with
that, but we haven't done much
to deal with

42:58.576 --> 43:00.611 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
trains or ferry boats, for
example.

43:00.645 --> 43:06.217 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Because of our
political system,
as you say, it's hard for our
leaders to -- political

43:06.250 --> 43:13.024 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
leaders to say candidly to the
American people
that there will always be a
threat out there,

43:13.057 --> 43:14.625 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that you cannot completely...

43:14.659 --> 43:16.461 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEVEN BRILL: President Obama
has tried to
do that.

43:16.494 --> 43:22.867 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And every time he's even in a
subtle way tried
to do that, where he has said --
and, indeed,

43:22.900 --> 43:30.274 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
his Department of Homeland
Security has implemented
really important mitigation
measures, really

43:30.308 --> 43:34.011 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
important, you know, recovery
measures if
there's an attack.

43:34.045 --> 43:39.484 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There was a drill in Boston just
a few months
before the bombing there.

43:39.517 --> 43:44.255 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when they did a report about
that drill
and how that had really helped
to save lives

43:44.288 --> 43:51.596 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
after the marathon bombing, he
was attacked
by Senator Coburn for putting
too much emphasis

43:51.629 --> 43:54.866 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on mitigation, and not enough on
prevention.

43:54.899 --> 44:00.738 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Now, that, to me, is the
equivalent of saying,
why do you have ambulances on
call?

44:00.771 --> 44:04.008 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Why don't you do something about
crime and
traffic safety?

44:04.041 --> 44:08.646 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, you try to prevent crime
and you try
to prevent car accidents, but
you have emergency

44:08.679 --> 44:10.615 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
rooms, you have ambulances.

44:10.648 --> 44:13.718 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You acknowledge the fact that
you're not going
to prevent all traffic
accidents.

44:13.751 --> 44:20.324 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We are not going to prevent all
terrorism,
especially if you define it as
someone being

44:20.358 --> 44:26.097 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
able to get an assault weapon,
which you can
do in this country, and claim to
be loyal

44:26.130 --> 44:28.466 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to ISIS or some organization
like that.

44:28.499 --> 44:32.203 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What would you
say to the next
leader of this country, the next
president

44:32.236 --> 44:35.473 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about what most needs to be done
to make this
country...

44:35.506 --> 44:37.275 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

44:37.308 --> 44:39.911 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVEN BRILL: Well, the first
thing that needs
not to be done is to declare war
on Muslims

44:39.944 --> 44:44.048 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or Islam, because that's exactly
what those
terrorists want.

44:44.081 --> 44:51.222 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
They want this to be the
apocalyptic, end-of-all-worlds
war between them and us.

44:51.255 --> 44:56.994 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And President Bush didn't take
the bait, and
President Obama has resisted
taking that bait.

44:57.028 --> 44:58.696 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Donald Trump campaigns on that.

44:58.729 --> 45:05.369 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it almost makes you think --
in fact,
it makes me think that ISIS
would love to

45:05.403 --> 45:10.408 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have someone like Trump be
president, because
they would get the fulfillment
of their dream,

45:10.441 --> 45:15.179 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which is to have the great
confrontation with
Western civilization.

45:15.212 --> 45:19.850 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The second thing is to keep
educating the
country.

45:19.884 --> 45:25.389 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
While doing everything we can to
prevent terrorism,
keep educating the country to
the reality

45:25.423 --> 45:31.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that there are going to be some
attacks, and
that doesn't mean it's the
apocalypse.

45:31.729 --> 45:33.698 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It doesn't mean we're weak.

45:33.731 --> 45:39.403 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Saying there are going to be
attacks doesn't
mean you're throwing in the
towel, but it

45:39.437 --> 45:40.938 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
means we have to be realistic.

45:40.972 --> 45:44.675 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, it's
certainly a provocative
piece.

45:44.709 --> 45:51.415 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's one that reminds us of how
complex the
challenges are, and they don't
get any simpler

45:51.449 --> 45:52.416 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
as time goes by.

45:52.450 --> 45:53.417 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
STEVEN BRILL: Thanks.

45:53.451 --> 45:54.418 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Steven Brill.

45:54.452 --> 45:58.022 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Are we any safer than we were on
9/11?

45:58.055 --> 46:03.527 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Thank you very much.

46:03.561 --> 46:09.000 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
STEVEN BRILL: You're welcome.

46:09.033 --> 46:17.541 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: A photography
museum is reopening
in a sleek new home in New York
City, with

46:17.575 --> 46:22.446 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
an exhibition to make you think
twice about
all the cameras that surround
us.

46:22.480 --> 46:24.415 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown has the story.

46:24.448 --> 46:29.787 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: A stark message
stops visitors
in their tracks at the threshold
of the International

46:29.820 --> 46:35.993 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Center of Photography's new
home: "By entering
this area, you consent to being
photographed,

46:36.027 --> 46:41.365 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
filmed and/or otherwise
recorded, and surrender
the right to the use of such
material throughout

46:41.399 --> 46:43.234 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the universe in perpetuity."

46:43.267 --> 46:48.205 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's what the museum's
first exhibition
in its brand-new space in Lower
Manhattan

46:48.239 --> 46:53.811 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
explores, the changing role of
privacy in
a world inundated with
surveillance and oversharing.

46:53.844 --> 46:56.614 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAULINE VERMARE, Associate
Curator, Public,
Private, Secret: What is your
secret life?

46:56.647 --> 46:58.482 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
How can you keep it secret?

46:58.516 --> 47:04.321 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that's one of the keys
of this exhibition
is really that, keeping your
privacy, but

47:04.355 --> 47:07.324 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
also making sure that your
secret life remains
your secret life.

47:07.358 --> 47:12.329 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Pauline Vermare
is the associate
curator of Public, Private,
Secret, a mix

47:12.363 --> 47:15.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of visual media, modern and
historical.

47:15.199 --> 47:21.372 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's this 1946 Yale Joel
photograph of
a couple through a two-way
mirror for a series

47:21.405 --> 47:27.311 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in "LIFE" magazine, and more
contemporary
surveillance art by Jill Magid,
who captured

47:27.344 --> 47:32.883 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
herself on surveillance cameras,
and Merry
Alpern, who secretly shot
through the bathroom

47:32.917 --> 47:37.088 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
window of a seedy sex club for
her "Dirty
Windows" series.

47:37.121 --> 47:43.327 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The museum itself has come a
long way from
its 1974 beginnings in a
Manhattan mansion

47:43.360 --> 47:47.431 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
under the direction of famed
Hungarian photographer
Cornell Capa.

47:47.465 --> 47:49.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Since then, the world of
photography has changed.

47:49.400 --> 47:52.303 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MARK LUBELL, Director,
International Center
of Photography: It is the most
Democratic

47:52.336 --> 47:53.504 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
format.

47:53.537 --> 47:55.072 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It is in the hands of all of us.

47:55.106 --> 47:58.008 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We all are now visually
communicating.

47:58.042 --> 48:02.646 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Mark Lubell is
the current
director of the museum, known as
the ICP.

48:02.680 --> 48:07.818 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's overseen an institutional
shift, from
photojournalism and art
photography to an

48:07.852 --> 48:12.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
embrace of today's digital media
landscape,
where cell phone cameras are
ubiquitous.

48:12.790 --> 48:18.362 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARK LUBELL: The big difference
is, it used
to be a few people taking images
that went

48:18.395 --> 48:20.264 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
out to millions.

48:20.297 --> 48:23.267 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And now it's millions and
millions of people
going out to millions and
millions of people.

48:23.300 --> 48:28.439 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that's a seismic shift
in the medium,
and it's something that we
should be looking

48:28.472 --> 48:30.274 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
at and exploring.

48:30.307 --> 48:34.211 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: In the inaugural
exhibition,
that means a sometimes jarring
juxtaposition

48:34.245 --> 48:36.013 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of images.

48:36.046 --> 48:38.783 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAULINE VERMARE: We start with
historical
precedents, and everything is
thrown together.

48:38.816 --> 48:40.951 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It's not like there's a
hierarchy.

48:40.985 --> 48:42.753 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Everything is at the same level.

48:42.787 --> 48:47.324 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: A lineup of
mid-20th century
mug shots taken by unknown
photographers sits

48:47.358 --> 48:52.363 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
just beneath portraits of four
Muslim women,
prisoners in a concentration
camp during the

48:52.396 --> 48:53.697 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Algerian War.

48:53.731 --> 48:56.901 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They were forced to pose without
their veils.

48:56.934 --> 48:58.736 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
In our own time, people expose
themselves.

48:58.769 --> 48:59.737 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
WOMAN: I'm not gay.

48:59.770 --> 49:00.738 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
MAN: I am gay.

49:00.771 --> 49:02.573 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
WOMAN: I am so gay.

49:02.606 --> 49:07.144 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Offering up
private thoughts
online, in the form of video
diaries available

49:07.178 --> 49:18.789 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to anyone.

49:18.823 --> 49:23.694 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Artist Natalie Bookchin sifted
through hundreds
of those and created an
installation titled

49:23.727 --> 49:25.529 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
"Testament."

49:25.563 --> 49:27.898 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NATALIE BOOKCHIN, Artist: I'm
choreographing
these moments and organizing
them to try to

49:27.932 --> 49:29.700 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
make some sense out of them.

49:29.733 --> 49:33.170 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that there's a sense,
first of all,
that this stuff is junk, right,
that it's

49:33.204 --> 49:36.574 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
throwaway, that we shouldn't
watch it, that
it's all just narcissistic, and
that it's

49:36.607 --> 49:38.876 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
kids that are doing silly things
with their
phone.

49:38.909 --> 49:42.213 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what I'm trying to show in
this work,
that it's not just kids, that
it's like -- it's

49:42.246 --> 49:43.681 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
sort of people.

49:43.714 --> 49:48.819 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You know, people are doing this,
old people,
young people, men, women.

49:48.853 --> 49:58.996 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: We see and hear
some subjects
alone, others in a kind of
chorus focused

49:59.029 --> 50:01.699 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
on a particular theme.

50:01.732 --> 50:04.768 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of her pieces examined
people who had
lost their jobs in the
recession.

50:04.802 --> 50:10.374 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NATALIE BOOKCHIN: I wanted in
the work to
both show the way that sort of
people were

50:10.407 --> 50:17.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
alone, in some way trying to
engage in a political
discussion or a social
discussion, something

50:17.281 --> 50:21.752 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that just happened that's really
bad, because
the economy is crashing and
people are losing

